<h1 id="building-a-blog-with-markdn">Building a Blog with Markdn</h1>
<p>In this tutorial, we'll build a complete blog using Markdn's content collections feature.</p>
<h2 id="step-1-define-your-collection">Step 1: Define Your Collection</h2>
<p>Start by creating a <code>collections.json</code> file that defines the schema for your blog posts:</p>
<pre><code class="language-json">{
  &quot;collections&quot;: {
    &quot;posts&quot;: {
      &quot;folder&quot;: &quot;Content/posts&quot;,
      &quot;schema&quot;: {
        &quot;properties&quot;: {
          &quot;title&quot;: { &quot;type&quot;: &quot;string&quot; },
          &quot;pubDate&quot;: { &quot;type&quot;: &quot;string&quot;, &quot;format&quot;: &quot;date-time&quot; },
          &quot;description&quot;: { &quot;type&quot;: &quot;string&quot; }
        },
        &quot;required&quot;: [&quot;title&quot;, &quot;pubDate&quot;]
      }
    }
  }
}
</code></pre>
<h2 id="step-2-create-content">Step 2: Create Content</h2>
<p>Add markdown files to your <code>Content/posts</code> directory with frontmatter:</p>
<pre><code class="language-markdown">---
title: &quot;My First Post&quot;
pubDate: 2025-11-01T10:00:00Z
description: &quot;This is my first blog post!&quot;
---

# Hello World

Welcome to my blog!
</code></pre>
<h2 id="step-3-query-your-collection">Step 3: Query Your Collection</h2>
<p>Use the generated content service to access your posts with full type safety:</p>
<pre><code class="language-csharp">var posts = contentService.GetCollection();
foreach (var post in posts)
{
    Console.WriteLine($&quot;{post.Title} - {post.PubDate}&quot;);
}
</code></pre>
<h2 id="conclusion">Conclusion</h2>
<p>Markdn makes it easy to build content-driven applications with type safety and great developer experience!</p>


